1
00:00:01,532 --> 00:00:18,612
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:18,896 --> 00:00:26,649
Namo tassa bhagavato arhato samma sambuddhassa.

3
00:00:27,370 --> 00:00:31,716
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:33,838 --> 00:00:40,549
So I thought this evening I'd tackle this thorny problem of social karma.

5
00:00:44,195 --> 00:00:46,878
Now, according to the Buddha,

6
00:00:47,500 --> 00:00:52,265
The karma that we own is the actions that we've performed.

7
00:00:52,826 --> 00:00:55,990
So these can be a thought, speech, or of course, actions.

8
00:00:57,292 --> 00:01:00,295
And they're all products of the will.

9
00:01:00,456 --> 00:01:02,978
It's the will that manifests them.

10
00:01:06,082 --> 00:01:07,584
Now, some of these are automatic.

11
00:01:07,906 --> 00:01:11,450
You know, we're just habitually thinking, doing things.

12
00:01:12,871 --> 00:01:16,917
Speech, of course, tends to be spontaneous or unfortunately impulsive.

13
00:01:18,819 --> 00:01:25,546
But then there are times when our responses are measured, when we have to think about what we're going to do.

14
00:01:27,149 --> 00:01:32,474
And those have often the greatest force within our personality.

15
00:01:36,597 --> 00:01:45,266
And what the importance of in the process of liberation is the ethical value or lack of it, of course.

16
00:01:46,326 --> 00:01:57,763
So these mental states, these sankara, are created by our decisions, moment to moment decisions, moment after moment, whether they are habitual or considered.

17
00:02:01,647 --> 00:02:08,257
Now, from that, it might be a little bit confusing to talk about social karma.

18
00:02:08,276 --> 00:02:11,401
I think it's better to talk about social conditioning.

19
00:02:11,722 --> 00:02:13,144
That makes a bit more sense, I think.

20
00:02:15,469 --> 00:02:18,473
So the fact is that we're embedded in our culture.

21
00:02:20,436 --> 00:02:30,788
I was visiting my brother down in the Isle of Wight and I was just watching this grandfather and grandmother taking their grandchild for a walk.

22
00:02:31,407 --> 00:02:38,776
And the child sort of stopped and turned around and lifting her arms to the air was obviously asking her grandfather to lift her up.

23
00:02:39,584 --> 00:02:43,069
And I could hear him saying, and.

24
00:02:43,471 --> 00:02:45,995
So she'd probably saying, lift me up.

25
00:02:46,235 --> 00:02:47,557
And he'd say, and.

26
00:02:48,780 --> 00:02:51,604
This went on for a little while.

27
00:02:51,625 --> 00:02:53,647
Unfortunately, my attention was taken away.

28
00:02:55,131 --> 00:03:00,580
And of course, I presume the grandmother was...

29
00:03:00,795 --> 00:03:13,373
cut in, just unable to bear the husband's unwillingness to respond to the child's pleas and prompted her by saying that magic word, please.

30
00:03:13,995 --> 00:03:21,445
So right there, he took it upon himself to teach the child that you have to say please.

31
00:03:25,412 --> 00:03:30,498
And usually, of course, as children, we totally accept the conditioning.

32
00:03:30,731 --> 00:03:38,704
It's only when we get to be naughty teenagers and later in life when we can reflect that we can see the conditioning that we have.

33
00:03:40,826 --> 00:03:44,673
We also, of course, pick up our prejudices.

34
00:03:45,754 --> 00:03:49,479
So I remember my niece and nephew were playing hospital.

35
00:03:50,842 --> 00:03:57,853
And my nephew was two years older than my niece, but they were both under seven, six and four.

36
00:03:57,935 --> 00:04:02,020
And of course, he said, I'll be the doctor and you'll be the nurse.

37
00:04:03,824 --> 00:04:09,233
And afterwards, I thought to myself, if she'd been the elder, would she have chosen to be the doctor?

38
00:04:11,697 --> 00:04:14,099
The same is true, of course, of racial prejudice.

39
00:04:16,043 --> 00:04:18,927
I was traveling to get back home.

40
00:04:19,848 --> 00:04:24,036
I had to go from Liverpool Street to Waterloo.

41
00:04:24,435 --> 00:04:25,478
And it really is a pain.

42
00:04:26,182 --> 00:04:29,267
And unfortunately, I ended up in Canary Wharf thinking it'd be easier.

43
00:04:30,269 --> 00:04:31,612
And I hadn't a clue where I was.

44
00:04:32,192 --> 00:04:34,297
And everybody said I should take the Jubilee line.

45
00:04:34,778 --> 00:04:38,584
So I was really stuck and everybody sort of disappeared apart from this black guy.

46
00:04:39,586 --> 00:04:42,271
So I asked him, you see, you know, how to get there.

47
00:04:43,031 --> 00:04:50,605
Now, as I asked him, I could feel this sort of anxiety that he might...

48
00:04:51,125 --> 00:04:59,199
reject my request in some way on the understanding, on my understanding, how he feels about white people.

49
00:05:00,581 --> 00:05:01,502
I mean, I was lucky.

50
00:05:01,543 --> 00:05:11,240
He happened to be working near the Jubilee line, which was something like a 15-minute walk away through I don't know how many streets.

51
00:05:12,201 --> 00:05:13,584
And he was very glad to take me.

52
00:05:13,824 --> 00:05:16,069
But I was interested in my experience.

53
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:22,286
in that idea that came up as I was asking him.

54
00:05:22,846 --> 00:05:27,052
I actually go out of my way to ask people of colour.

55
00:05:29,954 --> 00:05:30,314
Yeah.

56
00:05:32,197 --> 00:05:39,403
So the other one, of course, another one is, you know, we've just celebrated the Queen's Platinum Jubilee.

57
00:05:39,423 --> 00:05:45,009
And it's no doubt that she's been, you know, she's fulfilled that role of the monarch admirably.

58
00:05:45,817 --> 00:05:48,822
But have we ever actually considered the institution of monarchy?

59
00:05:49,362 --> 00:05:53,428
Now, I have to confess, I am a lifelong Republican.

60
00:05:56,372 --> 00:06:00,579
You have to forgive me for that.

61
00:06:00,600 --> 00:06:07,411
And that, of course, the monarchy, the institution, is the preserve of nobility, of privilege, the house of laws and all that.

62
00:06:07,430 --> 00:06:10,415
And it has an influence on us.

63
00:06:10,435 --> 00:06:14,000
It has an influence of how we see ourselves in society.

64
00:06:14,403 --> 00:06:15,904
How would you feel if you met her?

65
00:06:20,110 --> 00:06:29,822
Then, of course, something I've been banging on about these past couple of weeks is neoliberal, the neoliberal ideology and what it's done to us, made us much more selfish.

66
00:06:31,764 --> 00:06:41,136
So, for instance, in the NHS, instead of being patients, we were told that we were clients.

67
00:06:42,887 --> 00:06:49,218
And this meant that we moved away from an attitude of gratitude to entitlement.

68
00:06:50,220 --> 00:06:54,447
And the amount of suing of the NHS went up enormously.

69
00:06:55,168 --> 00:07:00,357
And it stands today at, yes, last year at £2.4 billion.

70
00:07:01,213 --> 00:07:08,401
Now, it's not that we shouldn't be compensated for poor treatment.

71
00:07:08,762 --> 00:07:09,744
That's not the problem.

72
00:07:10,384 --> 00:07:11,725
It's just where we're coming from.

73
00:07:11,786 --> 00:07:18,233
The entitled, the indignant entitled, as opposed to the injured patient.

74
00:07:19,334 --> 00:07:25,281
So how do you feel when you go for a service, when the bus doesn't arise?

75
00:07:26,242 --> 00:07:30,208
My parents would have just felt grateful.

76
00:07:31,370 --> 00:07:36,538
There's even now, I don't know whether you know about this, a defensive dentistry.

77
00:07:37,038 --> 00:07:42,728
Dentists won't do anything on your teeth unless they have proof of something wrong.

78
00:07:43,410 --> 00:07:50,420
They're absolutely scared of being sued for anything they do.

79
00:07:50,882 --> 00:07:55,850
There have been some really bad cases because of that.

80
00:07:55,870 --> 00:07:58,473
At a deeper level, of course, it's our race.

81
00:07:59,533 --> 00:08:07,004
How do we feel, you know, if we're black, how do we feel being in a white-dominated culture?

82
00:08:07,406 --> 00:08:11,552
Jews' unrelenting history of persecution.

83
00:08:12,913 --> 00:08:29,017
And then there's, of course, whites who are, at the moment, are being, shall we say, suggested by extreme Brexiteers with their shining luminary Boris that projects us as British, special, etc., etc.,

84
00:08:31,798 --> 00:08:36,452
So all this will be there within us.

85
00:08:36,933 --> 00:08:43,833
I mean, I came across real prejudice, shall we say, when I became a monk.

86
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:50,327
One time I walked into a shop and the assistant or the shopkeeper simply turned around and walked out.

87
00:08:51,089 --> 00:08:55,333
I was left just standing there until I realized she wasn't going to come out to serve me.

88
00:08:56,075 --> 00:08:59,438
And then there was a quite nasty occasion when I was at Dubai.

89
00:08:59,879 --> 00:09:06,868
So I was flying back from Sri Lanka when this drunken Englishman just went on and on about how stupid and ridiculous I looked.

90
00:09:10,746 --> 00:09:21,861
So it's catching, you know, how our personal conditioning, not the societal conditioning, how we are personally conditioned.

91
00:09:25,287 --> 00:09:31,936
And although we've had little choice in that conditioning, the fact of the matter is, it's us.

92
00:09:32,677 --> 00:09:39,605
We are an expression of our culture and it's our duty, it's our responsibility to accept that.

93
00:09:39,923 --> 00:09:42,327
and to do something about it when it's unwholesome.

94
00:09:44,231 --> 00:09:51,866
I mean, I have stressed the unwholesomeness within society, but obviously there's beauty too.

95
00:09:51,908 --> 00:09:58,000
And just mentioning the NHS, it's a product of a society of care.

96
00:10:01,253 --> 00:10:07,688
So everything around us is influencing us and we are influencing everybody, everything, everybody around us.

97
00:10:08,149 --> 00:10:15,447
So there's a certain responsibility there to make sure we know where we stand with all these issues.

98
00:10:16,879 --> 00:10:28,831
I mean, the Buddha has lots of advice for lay people in the Sigalavada Sutta, where he talks in detail about your relationship within a family.

99
00:10:28,851 --> 00:10:33,856
It's, of course, very patriarchal, but then he was a man of his time.

100
00:10:36,479 --> 00:10:45,148
And the monks were allowed to wander any way they wished, but during the rainy season, they had to come together

101
00:10:45,652 --> 00:10:51,461
And reestablish the fact that they were a community.

102
00:10:51,861 --> 00:10:59,413
And of course, he goes on to say, you know, how good companionship is the whole of the spiritual life.

103
00:10:59,433 --> 00:11:03,801
I mean, Ananda has come to the opinion that it's only half the holy life.

104
00:11:04,663 --> 00:11:08,688
And the Buddha replies, don't say that, Ananda, don't say that.

105
00:11:09,884 --> 00:11:18,099
Admirable friendship, admirable companionship, admirable camaraderie is actually the whole of the spiritual life.

106
00:11:18,119 --> 00:11:26,995
When a monk has admirable friends, people as friends, companions and comrades, he can be expected to develop and pursue the Noble Eightfold Path.

107
00:11:29,259 --> 00:11:31,825
And of course, he has also compassion.

108
00:11:32,563 --> 00:11:59,567
advice that he gave really to the who wanted to attack the Vajji Confederacy, pointing out that the nation's welfare was dependent on frequent meetings, that assemblies assemble and disperse peacefully and attend to their affairs in concord, that they do not enact new decrees or abolish old ones,

109
00:11:59,631 --> 00:12:03,126
and proceed in accordance with ancient constitutions.

110
00:12:06,662 --> 00:12:07,886
And...

111
00:12:08,221 --> 00:12:23,549
They respect, honor and esteem their elders, refrain from abducting women and maidens of good families, show respect, honor and esteem and veneration to shrines and look after their Arahats.

112
00:12:24,370 --> 00:12:30,162
So, of course, you can retranslate that for our own times.

113
00:12:30,630 --> 00:12:40,942
But here the Buddha is actually saying that the society we are in is, you know, we are dependent on it for our conditioning.

114
00:12:41,543 --> 00:12:43,046
We are responsible.

115
00:12:43,066 --> 00:12:49,173
Once we know we're conditioned, once we know our conditioning, we are responsible for it.

116
00:12:50,073 --> 00:12:54,278
And where we can, we, you know, develop a right conditioning.

117
00:12:54,700 --> 00:12:57,263
And in so doing, we affect the people around us.

118
00:12:58,677 --> 00:13:03,763
So that's about as far as I think social conditioning goes.

119
00:13:03,844 --> 00:13:06,567
So we can't really talk about social karma.

120
00:13:07,008 --> 00:13:21,044
We can only talk about our social conditioning within ourselves and then how we work with it, how we deal with it, and hopefully clear our hearts of anything that's negative.

121
00:13:23,808 --> 00:13:27,232
So I don't know whether that's created more confusion.

122
00:13:28,528 --> 00:13:35,761
or in some way brightened up this little dark area, which I don't think many people talk about.

123
00:13:36,964 --> 00:13:51,650
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, and that you will, by your endeavor to overcome all negative social conditioning, arise into the glory of Arahatship sooner rather than later.

